<p>With ICEBlock, the entire thing is simply no longer available. If you already have ICEBlock installed, the installed version still functions on your iPhone, but, until and if Apple changes its mind, there will be no further software updates and new users are unable to download it. Nor will current users be able to re-download the app on a new iPhoneâ€‰â€”â€‰and now is â€œnew iPhoneâ€ season. And, seemingly, there can be no web app (or Android) version of ICEBlock that offers the same level of anonymity as the native iOS versionâ€‰â€”â€‰with notifications, but without user accounts nor any database of device IDs for notifications that would be subject to subpoena from ICEBlock.</p>

<p>The gist of <a href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2025/07/26/iceblock-trust-apple">my second post on ICEBlock</a> from back in July is that ICEBlockâ€™s privacy-protecting architecture isnâ€™t magic. Itâ€™s based on trust in Apple itself. Joshua Aaron doesnâ€™t have access to ICEBlock usersâ€™ device IDs (let alone their personal identities), but ICEBlock can send push notifications to devices because Apple itself does know device IDs and usersâ€™ identities.</p>

